</i> and <i>Simpson</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Simon","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Clere was born in 1462, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Nicholas Clere, was 20 and his mother, Anne, was 16. He married Lady Emma of Colchester in 1486, in Colchester, Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1520, in Colchester, Essex, England, at the age of 58, and was buried in St Peter's Church, Colchester, Essex, England."},"et":{"1462–1520":"1462–1520","1466–Female":"1466–Surnud","1490–Male":"1490–Surnud","1500–1538":"1500–1538","1505–1538":"1505–1538","1505–1558":"1505–1558","1442–1500":"1442–1500","1446–Female":"1446–Surnud","15 December 1505":"15. detsember 1505","1462":"1462","Abt 1500":"umbes 1500","1490":"1490","Abt 1505":"umbes 1505","1558":"1558","1446":"1446","1500":"1500","1466":"1466","1520":"1520","1486":"1486","1442":"1442","1505":"1505","1538":"1538","St Peter's Church, Colchester, Essex, England":"St Peter's Church, Colchester, Essex, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Steyning, Sussex, England":"Steyning, Sussex, England","Dedham, Colchester, Essex